Dear Travis,

Make no mistake about it, right now Governor Mark Dayton and Barack Obama are on a war path to take away your right to keep and bear arms in Minnesota.

title: For Trade:  Colt Defender 1911 .45 w/ crimson trace, Wilson ambi safety and all kinds of other great gear. The total package!
postcontent:
I have a fully loaded Colt Defender lightweight 1911 .45 ACP. Comes with novak sights, Colt Upswept Beavertail Grip Safety, and gunsmith installed Wilson ambi safety. This pistol also comes with brand new Crimson Trace LG-404 instinctive activation laser grips, the best in the industry. I have the original case the pistol came in, all the original paperwork, plus three (possibly 4) 1911 magazines. These include one colt, two kimber and one generic mag. I also have the original grips the defender came with. Also, I have a nice (double?) mag belt clip. I will also include a custom molded LH Kydex holster as well as a soft material transport holster. This is a complete and all inclusive package for the discerning 1911 collector. This was my office gun and I absolutely love it, but like all things I eventually rire of my pieces and am now ready for a new toy. All told, there's easily $2,000 worth of hardware here. 

I'm not looking to sell this pistol, I'm looking for interesting things that go bang. I'd trade for a high end AR-15, an OBR, a nice carbine (we're not talking hi-points lol), or an AK47 or variant (no crappy stamped ones though). I'd also consider an AK or AR pistol, but not one of the junk variants. I'm also open to SBRs (short barrel rifles). I might also consider some super cool shotgun (Saiga 12, serbu shorty etc). One thing I don't have is a high end sniper rifle. If you have one kited out with scope, bipod etc, that would be of interest to me. I have most every pistol there is, but if you have something extra special, it can't hurt to mention it.

I'm in no rush to get rid of this piece, nor do I have any motivation to do so other than (as I said) an interesting trade. Let me know what you have, and maybe we can come to an agreement. I'm not really interested in adding any cash to the deal unless you have something like a KRISS carbine in which case obviously I'd add a little extra cash. If you're looking for an entry level 1911 this isn't the pistol for you.

title: For Sale:  Remington Nylon 66 .22LR
postcontent:
My dad is selling his Mohawk Brown Nylon 66.  If you don't know about these guns they were the first mass produced rifle that had a stock that wasn't wood.  The receiver and stock are both made of Nylon Zytel-101.  It is semi automatic tube fed where you load the rounds in through the butt of the gun and it's even self lubricating.  This rifles are known to be insanely reliable in any weather conditions and Remington even put a lifetime warranty on all the nylon material from cracking, breaking or even fading because back in those days if it wasn't wood people didn't trust it.  There is a period correct scope mounted on it right now that is a bit dusty.  The Nylon 66 is known to be very accurate with just the iron sights and even was famous for attaining the aerial shooting record.  It's in good shape with a few scratches that you could buff out if that's what you wanted.  It has just sat inside the house and I'm not even sure how long it's been since my dad has fired it and it looks like it's barely even been used.  
Email all offers and trades.

title: For Sale:  	 Adams & Deane Self Cocking 54-Bore Pistol / Hand guns For sale
postcontent:
This is a very early Adams patented self cocking or "automatic" revolver in 54 bore. The serial number is under 1000 and pre-dates the investment into Adams by a merchant bank. This is a significant revolver as it does not have a rammer but used spiked bullets pressed into a wad. This proved unsatisfactory as bullets could drop out of the cylinder much to the embarrassment (or demise) of the owner. Subsequently rammers were fitted as standard or often as a retrofit to earlier models. This revolver has not been touched.

The Adams revolver was a very significant development in British Firearms History and nice examples are scarce. Ultimately it was the quality of Adams' work and his contemporaries such as Tranter and Webley that lead to the demise of Colonel Colt's manufacturing aspirations in the United Kingdom.
The revolver has good mechanics and cocks, rotates and looks without problem and is tight. There is over 50% of the original finish remaining and even some case hardening evident. As can be seen the grips are very good and indicative of the quality of the revolver, there is a percussion cap compartment in the butt.
The full Adams & Deane address is engraved and nicely visible along the top strap and there is strong rifling in the bore.
Other than transitional revolvers this would have been about the first serious competition to Colt who was emerging with great success at this time.
A very pleasing revolver

title: For Sale/Trade:  Para Ordnance Warthog .45acp double stack 1911
postcontent:
Just testing the waters to see what is out there. I have no need nor am I in any kind of hurry to sell.

My cash sale price is $900 firm. (please refrain from emailing me with a lower offer, I will sell at the listed price if you want to buy it for cash, but I am primarily looking to trade for something else)

Only considering sale because it used to be my carry gun, but I have moved to carrying my XD-S instead.

The gun is a Para Ordnance Warthog, black finish, white dot rear sight and red fiber optic front sight. I am the second owner, purchased used at a gun shop, and have had it for about two years. Gun has had a professional trigger job performed when the fiber optic sight was installed, was done about a year ago, still have the receipt for the work performed, cost me $256.33, not counting the shipping costs. Trigger on the gun is excellent, almost zero take-up, crisp 4# break, and almost zero overtravel. Gun includes the factory plastic case, 2 ten round magazines and 1 thirteen round magazine with grip extension. The only negative on this gun is that because it has been carried there are light scratches and finish wear on the slide. The frame is in excellent condition, and a simple refinish of duracoat or cerakote on the slide would make the gun look brand new again (if the gun doesn't get sold or traded I will be doing that myself).

Between the cost of the gun and the trigger job and sight install I have just over $1000 wrapped up in this gun. I took into account what I have into the gun and what it would cost to have the slide refinished when determining my price/trade value.

title: For Sale:  Ruger 10/22 Takedown w/ 50 Rds
postcontent:
Selling a used 10/22 Takedown (Stainless Steel version), comes with the bag and everything that came with it originally (ruger 10 rd box magazine, scope mount, lock, all the papers, everything). I'll also throw in 50 rds of 22lr for free.

I require at the very least a VA driver license proving you are a resident and at least 18 years of age. Cash only. People with a CHP or active military will be given priority. Email me if you're interested.


Additional Info: I am the original owner, I've had it since early October. Took it to the range 3 times, put around 700 rds through it total. Cleaned receiver/bolt thoroughly after every trip, and I run a boresnake through the barrel as well. For that reason, the barrel has some gunk in it and could use a thorough cleaning with rod/brush/patches, I just liked the boresnake because it's quick and easy and seems to work well enough (never had a single issue in 700 rds). The factory rear sight snapped off, so I bought another from ruger and paid a local gunsmith to install it (it's very simple to tap it in but I just don't have the tools), and there are a couple minor nicks on the barrel from when he tapped it in. I have the rear sight a little bit adjusted to the left, but with the 50 rds I am including you should be able to zero it in however you want it. Like I said I've never had any issues with this rifle, it is accurate and most of all very fun to shoot.

Gun itself is in great shape, a couple very minor marks on it from normal use that you probably wouldn't notice unless I showed you. I clean it after every trip to the range so it has been looked after. The ammo included is 150 rds of PPU and 146 rds of Winchester, both 230gr FMJ. Beautiful gun, feels great to hold and shoot, completely reliable and accurate. This is also one of the rarer Springfield Loaded models that were made in the U.S. rather than Brazil. You can tell because of the Geneseo, IL stamp above the serial number, instead of the IMBEL, BRAZIL that you would find on most models below the Operator.

postcontent:
Heckler & Koch Caliber: 40 S&W Action: Double / Single Action Firearm / 3 Mags

All major metal components on the USP are corrosion-resistant. Outside metal surfaces are protected by H&K’s proprietary “hostile environment” nitride finish. Internal metal parts are coated with a Dow Corning anti-corrosion chemical to reduce friction and wear.

 The gunmaker tested the MK23′s recoil system with over 30k rounds of +P ammunition followed by 6k high pressure proof rounds. After disassembling the gun the Germans found no damage or excessive wear to any of the components.

 And then they did some more tests . . .

 The ballistic boffins froze the USP to −42 °C (−43.5 °F), fired it and then frozen it again. They heated it to 67 °C (152.6 °F) and fired it. They cycled between these extremes several times. They subjected USP to standard NATO mud and rain abuse. They immersed it in water and sprayed it with sea water. They dropped it from six feet, hammer first, onto a steel-backed concrete slab.

 H&K deliberately lodged a bullet in the barrel and then sent another one down the pipe. The second bullet cleared the obstruction producing only a minor bulge in the barrel. They loaded a full magazine and then fired the gun again with the bulging barrel. The resulting group measured less than 4 inches of deviation at 25 meters – a standard that  new guns would be lucky to hold but 90% do not.

 In short, Heckler & Koch , The selected gun by the US Seal Teams.
